      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that makes sense. so like, who actually has control over the money while it's in there? is it the realtor or is it totally separate from them? also what happens if one side tries to back out last minute?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The escrow account is typically managed by a neutral third-party company, such as a title company or a trust company, that's not affiliated with the realtor. They're essentially the \"bankers\" of the escrow account, making sure the money is held securely until the deal is closed. The realtor's role is more like a facilitator, helping to coordinate the transaction and ensuring that the necessary funds are transferred. If one side tries to back out last-minute, the escrow account can act as a \"brake\" to prevent the deal from falling apart. The escrow company can hold the funds until the deal is finalized or can return them to the parties involved if the deal falls through. This way, neither side can just \"pull the plug\" on the deal without facing potential consequences.",
